Record.CAVI-Inscriptions: A: Αθεναια. Περ[ρ]ευς, retr. C: Αρεπυια.

Record.CAVI-Lemma: Frs. of BF pot (three frs.). From Athens. Nettos Painter. Last quarter seventh.
Record.CAVI-Subject: Wings; remains of a woman. On the neck: large floral.
Record.CAVI-Inscriptions: On top of the rim (fr. a), Gr. at broken edge: Graef: [---γλαυκο]πιδι ϙ[ορει ---](?)(2) I read: parts of two lines: [---](.)(.)(.)[---] | [---]φ̣ιδιωι[---], retr.{3}.
Record.CAVI-Comments: Lightly incised and in part unclear. Not contemporary with the pot, a casual Gr., not a dedication; Graef's interpretation is wrong. - Correspondence 1984-85 between Boegehold, Ludger Hunnekens and myself about this text: H. made a dr. which shows a double circle, like the omega from Phlius. B. in answer suggested: αι λωι διϙ[---]. H. replied with a new dr. and suggested the ff. traces: [---]ι(ω)ιδι(ϙ)[---], saying that there is an unexplained line attached to the omega's upper circle and that the last letter could be phi, psi or koppa. I suggested in 1985 that one might read the inscription retr.: [---]φιδιωι, with `Phlian' omega. I now think that there are three bottom verticals coming down from the break above, so that we have remains of two lines. H. rightly thinks that this Gr. cannot be contemporary with the pot. It is no doubt a casual notation. The omega is not Attic (Phlius?).
Record.CAVI-Footnotes: {1} Nettos Painter fused with Chimaera Painter. {2} The letters broken at the top. Graef is uncertain about the reading: "mit Verschreibung." {3} The first line perhaps not retr., as the last letter may have the end of a short vertical to the right, so perhaps a pi. Boustrophedon? The three letters (.) are bottom verticals.
